<HEAD>Outline of Bennett's Model Elementary School Curriculum</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bennett-Elementary Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is an overview of Secretary William J.
Bennett's suggested elementary school curriculum in seven primary
subjects:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ENGLISH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Kindergarten through Grade 3: Introduction to reading and
writing, including phonics, silent and oral reading, basic rules of
grammar and spelling, vocabulary, writing and penmanship,
composition and library skills.
   Grades 4 through 6: Introduction to critical reading, including
children's literature, book reports, advanced grammar, spelling and
vocabulary and composition skills.
   Grade 7: Survey of elementary grammar and composition.
   Grade 8: Survey of elementary literary analysis.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOCIAL STUDIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   K through 3: Introduction to history, geography and civics
(significant Americans, explorers, native Americans, American
holidays, customs and symbols; citizenship and landscape, climate
and mapwork).
   Grade 4: U.S. history to Civil War.
   Grade 5: U.S. history since 1865.
   Grade 6: World history to the Middle Ages.
   Grade 7: World history from the Middle Ages to 1900.
   Grade 8: World geography and U.S. constitutional government.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MATHEMATICS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   K through 3: Introduction to mathematics (numbers, basic
operations, fractions and decimals, rounding, geometric shapes,
measurement, bar graphs, estimation and elementary statistics.)
   Grades 4-6: Intermediate arithmetic and geometry (number theory,
negative numbers, percentages, exponents, line graphs, the
Pythagorean theorem and basic probability).
   Grades 7-8: General math, pre-algebra and algebra (two of the
three).
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SCIENCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   K through 3: Introduction to science (plants and animals, the
food chain, the solar system, rocks and minerals, weather, magnets,
energy and motion, properties of matter and simple experiments).
   Grade 4: Earth science and other topics.
   Grade 5: Life science and other topics.
   Grade 6: Physical science and other topics.
   Grade 7: Biology.
   Grade 8: Chemistry and physics.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FOREIGN LANGUAGE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   K through 3: Optional.
   Grades 4-6: Introduction to foreign language (basic vocabulary,
grammar, reading, writing, conversation and cultural material).
   Grades 7-8: Two years of formal language study strongly
recommended (equivalent to a one-year high school course).
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FINE ARTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   K through 3: Music and visual art (songs, recordings, musical
sounds and instruments, painting, craftmaking and visual effects).
   Grades 4-6: Music and visual art (great composers, musical
styles and forms, elementary music theory, great painters,
interpretation of art and creative projects.
   Grades 7-8: Music appreciation and art appreciation (one
semester of each).
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PHYSICAL EDUCATION@HEALTH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   K through 3: Body control, fitness, sports, games and exercises,
sportsmanship, safety, hygiene, nutrition and drug prevention
education.
   Grades 4-6: Team and individual sports, first aid, drug
prevention education and appropriate sex education.
   Grades 7-8: Strategy in team sports, gymnastics, aerobics,
self-assessment for health, drug prevention and sex education.
</TEXT>
